## 3. "No Eyes, No Ears": Dispossession, Not Abstraction

The structural center of the Heart Sūtra is the great negation. Avalokiteśvara systematically strips away the "I": "no eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, mind; no sight, sound, smell, taste, touch, thought."[^16]

Ontologically, this is the doctrine of *śūnyatā*---the claim that phenomena lack inherent existence (*svabhāva*). They are empty of any permanent, unchanging essence. But there's another way to hear this, especially if your body is already rendered hypervisible by a surveilling state.

Ralph Ellison understood the weight of the gaze. He opened *Invisible Man* with a paradox: "I am invisible, understand, simply because people refuse to see me."[^17] Ellison's narrator isn't a ghost. He's a man of "flesh and bone." But his invisibility is a social negation. A gaze that denies his heart. He finds freedom in a basement lit by stolen electricity. He becomes *ungraspable*.

The Heart Sūtra's negations are a practice of **strategic dispossession**. "No eyes, no ears, no body." To hear this while hyper-embodied as a target is an invitation. It dissolves the coordinates the system uses to find us.

I see this as a counter to what Orlando Patterson called "social death."[^18][^19] The enslaved person is rendered "no-one." Natally alienated. Generally dishonored. Under the law, they are a void.

The Heart Sūtra meets social death with **ontological defiance**. It takes this "no-one" and turns it into a superpower. If the system grants you only social death, you lean into the groundlessness. You realize the "social self" was always a lie. You let go of the "I" that can be owned or dishonored. You find a freedom the system didn't give and can't take back. You turn the "no-one" of the law into the ungraspability of the Dharma.

Think of it as a **ballistic strategy**. Life in a racialized state is a shower of arrows. Physical. Psychological. Legal. If you have a solid self, those arrows have a target. Every insult, every threat lodges in the "I." But if you dissolve the target? The arrows still come. But they pass right through. You become the sky. You can't wound the blue.

"When you go all the way down, you find there ain't no bottom to stand on. And that's the freedom." This is the language of survival. Life brings the suffering---but it passes right through. Like shooting arrows at the sky.[^20]

Ellison's narrator finds that "the very invisibility that I have found so difficult to accept is my greatest weapon." This is the heart of the "Emptiness Blues." It's the realization that if the system cannot "see" your humanity, it also cannot fully "contain" your spirit. The void is not where you disappear; it's where you become unfixable. It's what Saidiya Hartman calls a "beautiful experiment" in living otherwise.[^21]

The phenomenology of this move deserves careful attention. When Ellison's invisible man descends into his basement, he does not cease to exist. He continues to eat, sleep, dream, and---crucially---write. The invisibility that was imposed upon him becomes a condition he *inhabits*, and in inhabiting it, he transforms it from a curse into a vantage point. Similarly, the Heart Sūtra's negations do not abolish experience; they abolish the *reification* of experience. The practitioner who realizes "no eyes, no ears" does not become blind and deaf. She sees and hears with new clarity, freed from the compulsive identification of "I" with the seeing and hearing.

Zenju Earthlyn Manuel warns that this shouldn't be an escape into "color-blindness." In *The Way of Tenderness*, she argues that the realization of no-self doesn't erase race or gender. It allows us to hold them lightly.[^22] Race is real in its effects, but empty in its essence. The negations of the Sūtra don't deny the wounds of race; they deny the ontological solidity of the categories on which oppression depends.

The Sūtra promises "no obstructions" (*āvaraṇa*). In a Blues context, the greatest obstruction is the social position we're forced to inhabit---the assigned space in a hierarchy that limits what we can see or be. Emptiness dissolves that position. It's a form of political consciousness. It's the recognition that the categories we are sorted into are not given. They are made. And what is made can be unmade.

The phrase "no obstructions" (*āvaraṇa* in Sanskrit) merits further reflection. What are the obstructions that the Heart Sūtra dissolves? In the Tibetan commentarial tradition, following Haribhadra and later the *tengyur* exegetes, they are typically identified as the "two obscurations": the obscuration of afflictive emotions (*kleśāvaraṇa*) and the obscuration of cognitive errors (*jñeyāvaraṇa*).[^44] But in the context of a Blues hermeneutic, we might add a third: the obscuration of social position—the way that one's assigned place in a hierarchical system limits what one can see, think, and do. The realization of emptiness, from this angle, is not only a matter of personal psychology; it is a form of political consciousness. It is the recognition that the categories by which we are sorted and ranked are not given but made—and what is made can be unmade.

## 4. Emptiness as Mobility, Not Void

Don't confuse *śūnyatā* with nihilism. That's a domesticated reading for those who have the luxury of a stable ground. Scholars debate whether the Sūtra's negations are primarily ontological, epistemological, or soteriological; this article emphasizes *śūnyatā's* pragmatic—that is, soteriological—function as survival technology. For those surviving the Mississippi Delta, emptiness wasn't a void. It was **hypermobility**. It was the refusal to be nailed down by the categories of the state.

### Fluidity, Not Void

Clyde Woods documented how Black communities, stripped of land and rights, survived by moving. In this context, emptiness is fluidity. It's the knowledge that if you can't own the ground, you better learn to float. A void is static. Fluidity is a river. An empty self is a self freed from the rigidity that makes it breakable. It is the difference between an iron bar and a stream of water. The bar can be bent and broken. The water just flows around the obstruction and keeps on going toward the sea.

"Now that don't mean it don't exist. It means it flows like water in a river." This is the *śūnyatā* of survival. It's what Thich Nhat Hanh describes in *The Heart of Understanding* using the metaphor of the wave and the water: a wave does not need to die to become water because it *is* water, empty of a separate self but full of watery nature.[^23] This captures the Sūtra's teaching on the non-duality of form and emptiness. As famously popularized by Jon Kabat-Zinn but originating with Swami Satchidananda, "you can't stop the waves, but you can learn to surf."[^24] In the Delta, the Sūtra teaches us how to ride the waves of history without being drowned by the fear of its weight.

### The Madhyamaka Anchor

I see the roots in Nāgārjuna's Madhyamaka. This is the rigorous anchor. It is the doctrine of the **Two Truths**. One truth: the racialized violence of the Delta. The hounds. The sheriffs. The burning houses. The "Blues Block" where every exit is a trap. This is profoundly real in its effects. It is the "Conventional Truth" (*saṃvṛti-satya*) of a world gone wrong. The other truth: the ontological categories on which that violence depends are empty. This isn't a bypass. It's an inhabitation. You live in both registers at once. You feel the heat of the fire, but you know the fire has no soul.

The Two Truths doctrine is essential here because it prevents the misreading that plagues so much popular Buddhism: the assumption that "emptiness" means "nothing matters." The conventional truth of suffering is fully real at its own level. The arrows are sharp. The hounds have teeth. The Madhyamaka point is that these phenomena lack *inherent* existence—they are dependently originated, not self-existent—which means they can be transformed. The Two Truths are not two separate realities, but two ways of seeing one reality. As Nāgārjuna writes in *Mūlamadhyamakakārikā* 24.10: "Without relying on the conventional, the ultimate cannot be taught; without understanding the ultimate, liberation is not attained."[^25] To inhabit the Blues Block is to know its conventional reality with full visceral intensity while simultaneously recognizing its ultimate emptiness.

In the *Mūlamadhyamakakārikā*, Nāgārjuna argues that things are empty *because* they are dependently originated.[^25a] They exist only in relation. To find freedom, you must identify the **Object of Negation** (*dgag bya*). This is the central methodological question of Madhyamaka praxis: what exactly is being negated? The answer is *svabhāva*—intrinsic nature, independent being, essence that exists from its own side without depending on causes, conditions, or conceptual imputation.

This is exactly what "Plantation Power" tries to nail onto the Black body: a fixed, essential "thingness." A solidity that can be owned, traded, and discarded. The racial category functions as if it were *svabhāva*—an indelible mark that defines the person's being. Madhyamaka proves that such solidity is a metaphysical lie. The "Negro" of the law is not an ultimate reality; it is a violent, dependent construction. The Object of Negation is not the person, not the body, not even the experience of suffering—it is the *reification* of these into something permanent, fixed, and target-able. When the Sūtra says "no eyes, no ears," it is negating the *svabhāva* of the sense-bases, not the conventional reality of seeing and hearing. The practice is surgical: it removes the tumor of essentialism while leaving the living tissue intact.

It's the **logic of the crossroads**—the *catuṣkoṭi* (tetralemma), a structure that refutes all extremes. Are we here? No. Are we there? No. Both? No. Neither? No. At the crossroads, we are the transit itself. The *catuṣkoṭi* is not merely a logical exercise; it is a liberation technology. By refusing all four positions, it dismantles the binary thinking (*vikalpa*) that locks phenomena into fixed categories. When Robert Johnson sings about "standing at the crossroads," he's in the middle of this tetralemma. He's all positions and none of them. He's in motion. The Devil may offer a deal, but the crossroads itself is the place where deals dissolve—where the fixed self that could sign a contract reveals itself as empty.

Nāgārjuna wasn't trying to build a new absolute. He was trying to point to the relational nature of everything. Emptiness itself is empty. It's a pointer, not a destination. If we treat emptiness as a "thing," we've missed the point. It's the *absence* of "thing-ness" that allows for the possibility of change.

For the dispossessed, this is a vital insight. If "The Negro" or "The Convict" were fixed, ontological categories, there would be no hope. But if those categories are empty—if they are merely the result of a specific, violent set of relationships—then they can be dismantled. The emptiness of the category is the beginning of the freedom of the person.

### The Crossroads and the Mojo

Houston Baker's theory of the Blues as a "matrix" fits perfectly here. He describes the Blues as a site of "generative uncertainty"---a railroad crossing where meanings are constantly reconfigured.[^26]

The railroad crossing is a potent symbol in the Black imagination. It's where the "underground railroad" forged its way to freedom; it's where the "Jim Crow" cars were detached; it's where the physical landscape of the South was sliced open by the machinery of capital. To stand at the crossing is to stand at the point where the personal track (your life) hits the historical track (the system).

The Blues happens in the middle of that collision. That uncertainty is exactly what *śūnyatā* describes. It's not a hole in reality; it's the condition that allows any form to emerge at all. If the crossing were "solid"---if it were a fixed destination---there would be no movement. It's only because the crossing is an empty space of transit that the train can pass through.

This brings us to the **emptiness of historical records**. Saidiya Hartman and Christina Sharpe have both written about the "wake" of slavery---the way the trauma of the past continues to structure the present.[^27] Sharpe's concept of "wake work"---the labor of living in the ongoing disaster of slavery's afterlife---names precisely what the Sūtra offers: not escape from the wake, but a way to breathe inside it.[^41] In a Madhyamaka framework, the "history" that binds us is also empty. It is not a solid, unchanging fate. It is a set of conditions. By recognizing the emptiness of the past, we don't erase it; we stop it from being a cage. We move from being "objects" of history to being "subjects" who can remix it.

For people whose lives are perpetually precarious, this is liberating. It says: *you are not the category they forced you into*. The roles of slave or convict are empty of inherent existence. They are what Nāgārjuna would call "dependently originated"---they exist only in relation to a specific, violent set of conditions. And if the conditions are empty, the roles are porous.

This is the secret power of the "Mojo." In the Blues, a Mojo isn't just a bag of roots; it's a performance of agency. When Muddy Waters sings about his mojo, he's doing exactly what Avalokiteśvara does—dissolving the "obstructions" through a sonic assertion of power. Waters is saying that despite the legal and social negations, there is a core of "generative uncertainty" that can't be touched. A Mojo is a "signifying" object---it claims a power that isn't recognized by the system. It is a piece of emptiness that you carry in your pocket to remind you that the system is a lie.

Albert Murray argued that the function of the Blues was to "stomp" the blues---to turn suffering into rhythmic engagement.[^28] Stomping is work---a form of embodied contemplation that asserts presence not in spite of the void, but as its rhythmic expression. This aligns with what Howard Thurman described as "centering down" to find the "movement of the Spirit" in the middle of a lull in the rhythm of daily doing.[^29] In his analysis of Turner's 2009 album *Beyond*, Ralph H. Craig III argues that her performance functions as a **sonic liturgy**, through which Turner takes on the role of an authoritative Black Buddhist teacher by creating a site of transformative spiritual engagement.[^30] We see this same insistence in Pamela Ayo Yetunde's analysis of Prince, where spiritual devotion and rhythmic audacity combine to navigate the "thing called life" with both vulnerability and power.[^31]

The Heart Sūtra is doing the same. Its negations are clearings. They strip away the reifications that make suffering stick. Fred Moten theorizes the "break" as the generative rupture where Black sound escapes capture---a sonic analogue to the Sūtra's systematic negations.[^42] What remains isn't nothing. It's everything, minus the illusion of fixity. "Form is emptiness, emptiness is form"---the flowing world and the truth of its flow are the same thing. This is a radical non-duality that refuses to separate the sacred from the grit. The Mojo is the emptiness in your pocket; the Sūtra is the emptiness in your breath. Both are tools for stayin' free when the world wants you bound.

The Blues refuses to separate theory from practice. When Muddy Waters sings about his mojo, he's performing it into being. When you chant the Heart Sūtra, you aren't stating a fact. You're participating in a reality.

